        "heading": "Tiered Levy Rates and the Dependency Ratio Ceiling",
        "level": 2,
        "body": "The levy is not a flat rate per worker — it steps up as a business's ratio of foreign to local workers rises, under what MOM calls the Dependency Ratio Ceiling (DRC), and this tiering catches out fast-growing SMBs that scale headcount by hiring foreign workers first. A commercial cleaning services company grew from 8 to 35 staff in 18 months, hiring almost entirely work-permit holders because local applicants for the roles were scarce. What the owner hadn't tracked was that once the foreign worker proportion crossed the sector's basic DRC tier, every additional foreign hire beyond that tier was levied at a materially higher \"Tier 2\" rate — in their services-sector case, a jump from the basic rate to a second-tier rate roughly SGD 200/month higher per worker beyond the quota. By the time the owner reviewed the levy bill against their MOM quota allocation, 9 of their 28 foreign workers were being charged at the higher tier, adding almost SGD 1,800/month in levy cost that hadn't been budgeted because nobody had modelled the DRC threshold when the hiring plan was made. The fix going forward was to model each new foreign hire against the current quota utilisation before extending an offer, not after the levy bill arrived."
