        "body": "Reducing parts inventory too aggressively creates a different, often more expensive problem than overstocking: a customer walks in with a broken screen, you don't have the part in stock, and they walk straight to a competitor down the row who does. A phone and laptop repair shop in a busy electronics mall cut their screen inventory too sharply after reading generic inventory optimisation advice, aiming purely for faster turnover without weighing the cost of a stockout against the modest carrying cost of holding an extra unit. Within six weeks, the shop tracked eleven walk-in customers who left without a repair because a common screen model wasn't in stock — and given that mall's dense cluster of competing repair kiosks, every one of those customers almost certainly completed their repair at a competitor within the same building, a total loss of the transaction plus the lost opportunity for a repeat customer relationship. The shop recalibrated by keeping their genuinely high-turnover items (the top 15–20 SKUs covering the most common phone models in the local market) at a slightly higher safety stock than pure turnover math would suggest, while applying aggressive just-in-time ordering only to lower-volume, less commonly requested parts. The right inventory target isn't a single turnover number applied uniformly — it's a stockout-cost-weighted target that varies by how walkable the competition is and how price-sensitive customers are to waiting even a single day for a part."
